Poet and storyteller Gcina Mhlophe speaks on the importance of the awareness of linguistic diversity. Courtsey #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - International Mother Language Day is aimed at the promotion of multilingualism and cultural diversity. The day is celebrated annually on February 21. Director of GcinaMasiko Arts and Heritage Trust Gcina Mhlophe said it is important to preserve indigenous languages for the next generation. READ: Mother tongues the key to preserving heritage "It is up to us to save the languages, to speak them, to celebrate them and to make sure that our children and their children will hear them. To hear the musicality, the magic and the power in our languages", said Mhlophe. According to the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization this year's theme is "languages without borders."